node.text:
I recently started following this bomb.com self help coach on my personal Instagram account. @therealjoirizarry 

Her daily convos/advice/ viewpoints are spot on in this stage of growth and healing. 

This particular post resonates with me as I started setting hella boundaries. Now I can identify that empty feeling, the loss that she speaks of. Maybe you can relate?

We strive to be the most authentic mental health Instagram on the platform and will always keep it 100% with you all. I’m proud of the decisions the athletes made in the Olympics. - @tanner_hamilton22

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by A Safe Place Inside Your Head on August 01, 2021 tagging @deanapanza, and @traumaandaddictionrecovery. May be an image of text that says 'If you were parentified as a child, as an adult you might: like to feel in control feel overly responsible for things outside of your control be the caregiver of your friends or relationships struggle to trust others be very self reliant struggle to ask for help sacrafice your needs for others feel unappreciated for all you take on struggle to play and let loose struggle to remember feeling like a kid @deanapanza'.

node.text:
All. Of. These. 

I was the oldest of six children, that I literally raised for my parents, including myself, and including them. 

It’s good to have a name to put with what happened. Being “parentified” puts the blame on the abusive trauma that occurred and takes the onus off me. - @therealjoirizarry 

📸 @deanapanza 

@traumaandaddictionrecovery 

Parentification occurs when we are forced to assume the role of adult as children. This can occur for many different reasons and show up in many different ways.
⠀⠀
Often times, connecting with our inner child can help us heal. Showing up for little us by listening to what we needed, supporting little us, and being the adult we needed then can be so powerful.
⠀⠀

node.text:
TW: Suicide

I know it’s dark. But it’s true. 

If you don’t know I lost my son to death by suicide 11 years ago. The @asafeplaceinsideyourhead family of @tanner_hamilton22 @atxlien and @annmarie_is_social have spent the last two years reminding you that you are not alone, and that you are seen and heard. And also that suicide is not the answer. 

The @asafeplaceinsideyourhead community reaches worldwide and the way you guys engage to help others, cheer each other on, and provide helpful advice is mind blowing. Never in our wildest dreams did we expect this is what it would be like. 

Keep on fighting the good fight, warriors, it’s hard for the sufferers of mental health issues and mental illness. Let’s keep the conversation going and end the stigma. 

Stop 🛑 suicide. 

In this post we honor Kenny brother to @tanner_hamilton22 @atxlien, nephew to @annmarie_is_social and my son. - @therealjoirizarry 

Feel free to honor someone you have loved and lost below 👇🏼

@wherethemobat

A couple and their plants are still a family. You dont need kids just to be called a family.'.

node.text:
👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼

The family unit looks so different these days. And personally, for me family looks different too. I have one granddaughter and am perfectly fine with that, I actually discourage my children to have children, fight me! 

UNPOPULAR OPINION… you do you with the family/framily that looks good and is manageable to you. Don’t fall into the social “norms” of what you should do and do what you want to do.

Your mental health will thank you. - @therealjoirizarry 

@anxietytwitter

I recently started following this bomb.com self help coach on my personal Instagram account. @therealjoirizarry 

Her daily convos/advice/ viewpoints are spot on in this stage of growth and healing. 

This particular post resonates with me as I started setting hella boundaries. Now I can identify that empty feeling, the loss that she speaks of. Maybe you can relate?
